The Air India bombings trial involves Sikh immigrants Bagri and Malik, accused of plotting the attack in 1985.
Prosecutors argue they were part of a conspiracy to bomb Air India jets, resulting in 331 deaths.
Witnesses claim the defendants confessed, with motives rooted in seeking revenge for the 1984 Golden Temple attack.
Bagri and Malik's defense teams dispute the evidence, highlighting inconsistencies and political agendas.
The trial, spanning 202 days with 113 witnesses, underscores the complexities and controversies surrounding the case.
Despite lacking direct evidence, the prosecution aims to prove the defendants' guilt beyond a reasonable doubt.
